Wick Geometry Channel Project Summary
Overview
This document summarizes the channel-detection methodology, the requested logic changes, and the key outcomes of the conversation around converting the current indicator into an outside-in channel finder while preserving the existing script structure.

Core Methodology
The channel methodology is based on an outside-in view of structure rather than a regression-first approach. The true outer rails are defined by the extreme pivot trendlines at the extremities, while the density of pivots inside those rails reveals internal rails and the midpoint.

The price action itself is intended to dictate structure and thresholds, rather than user-defined or arbitrary variables. Inner rails are inferred from the internal distribution of pivot points, and the midpoint is only meaningful when confirmed by that internal pivot density.

A key structural idea is that an old outer rail can become the midline of a newly expanded wider channel when price breaks into a larger structure. In this model, channels are fractal: what is an outer boundary at one scale can become an internal rail at the next scale up.

Channel Logic Priorities
The preferred hierarchy is:

Outer rails first, from extreme pivot pairs.

Internal pivot density second, to reveal inner rails and the midpoint.

The midpoint is not the anchor of the geometry; it is a derived internal structural line.

Angle quality matters more than generic containment or arbitrary filtering.

The user’s conceptual model is that the scoring defines the angle, the outer trendline defines the width, and the equidistant opposite side becomes the predicted rail.
 This keeps the geometry anchored in price structure rather than a best-fit regression line.

Requested Code Changes
The requested code changes were framed as patches, not a rewrite from scratch. The user explicitly wanted the current indicator preserved, with the logic fixed without introducing undeclared variables, unnecessary thresholds, or unstable Pine behavior.

Patch 1
Replace the current regression-first slope selection with slope candidates derived from same-side extreme pivot pairs. The preferred winner is the slope that aligns best with the internally derived midpoint, rather than the slope with the most weak touches.

The user rejected arbitrary threshold variables and wanted the price structure itself to determine which candidate slope is valid. A slope with more weak touches should lose to one with stronger midline coherence if the internal pivot structure supports it.

Patch 2
Any rail with 3 or more touches should persist as a separate structural trendline, even if it does not win the main channel selection. These lines should exist concurrently with the active channel rather than being discarded as failed candidates.

This means a confirmed 3-touch rail is not merely a rejected channel candidate; it is a valid piece of structure in its own right. The orphan rail concept was meant to preserve these confirmed lines as permanent concurrent drawings.

Patch 3
The wider outer rail and its expanded zone should be visually prominent. The widened outer rail is considered the most important line and should be clearly seen, with the shading preserved to show the expanded width.

Visual Hierarchy Preferences
The outer expanded rail should be the strongest visual object because it represents the extreme structural boundary. The user wanted it shaded and visually obvious, rather than visually subordinate to inner or midpoint lines.

The concurrent 3-touch orphan rails were intended to remain visible as structural lines, but still secondary to the winning outer channel boundary. The key distinction was meant to be structural status, not arbitrary style changes detached from the logic.

Additional Implementation Constraints
The user strongly preferred:

No approval requests or confirmation loops in the workflow.

No arbitrary threshold variables controlling structure.

No guesswork or speculative rewrites beyond explicitly requested changes.

Delivery as a full .pine file rather than partial snippets or placeholder outputs.

The user also emphasized Pine-specific robustness: no undeclared variables, no 5000 bars back errors, and no malformed newline or string formatting errors.

Summary Of The Conversation
The conversation focused on converting the current TradingView indicator into an outside-in channel finder while keeping the existing codebase intact. There was repeated discussion of replacing the regression-first approach with pivot-derived outer rails, using internal pivot density to derive inner rails and the midpoint, and preserving 3-touch rails as concurrent structural drawings.

A major point of friction was file access and delivery rather than the underlying methodology.
 The conversation repeatedly circled around GitHub access, attached files, approval-window glitches, and the inability to directly patch and return the full Pine source from the available conversation-log artifact.

Despite that delivery failure, the methodology itself became much clearer during the discussion. The final conceptual position was consistent: outer extremes define the true rails, internal pivot density defines the inner rails and midpoint, price dictates structure, and confirmed 3-touch rails remain valid even when they do not win the active channel.

